Package gw.api.system.logging.structuredlogger

Interface IStructuredLogger

All Known Implementing Classes:
StructuredLoggerImpl
public interface IStructuredLogger
Interface providing a contract for implementation of the Structured Logger... ...brought into platform from a previously published SurePath Content component

This interface will be implemented by a Java version of the Structured Logger... ...that itself will then be extended by a Gosu class provided via CBC.

    • logTrace

      LogData logTrace(@Nonnull String msg, Exception ex, List<Object> objects, Map<String,Object> parameters, String errorCode, String methodClazz, String methodName, boolean lightLog)
      Log a trace message.
      Parameters:
      msg - the log message.
      ex - the exception associated with this logging statement, if any
      objects - an optional list of objects, entities, or BoundPropertyReferences to add to the log message.
      parameters - an optional map of additional key/value pairs to add to the log message.
      errorCode - an optional parameter that allows you to inject a business or error code into the resulting output. This will be found in the variable contextMap and will be under the key "errorCode" in the map. The MDC will also be checked for this in case you set it in MDC.
      methodClazz - an optional parameter that is an alternative to passing the feature reference "Method". Using methodClazz and MethodName which are both strings will remove any performance implications in using the parameter "method". Use this in loops, batches and performance sensitive code. The downside however is that any code refactoring will have to remember to update the logging statements.
      methodName - an optional parameter that is an alternative to passing the feature reference "method". Used in combination with methodClazz (see description of methodClazz)
      lightLog - an optional boolean which indicates if you want to use lightLogging. Light logging only outputs the message, userId and serverId for when you are doing specific tracing or info messages, to keep the output minimal
      Returns:
      logged data, null if trace level logging is disabled

    • executeWithLoggingContext

      void executeWithLoggingContext(Runnable block, Map<String,String> parameters, boolean includeTiming)
      Sets logging context, executes an operation, and then cleans up logging context Optionally includes start and end timing as well as elapsed time If including start and end timing, elapsed time will be logged from the original start time for each logging statement naturally included in the executable code block. A final log statement at info level will also be provided to show the total execution time at the very end If including start and end timing, it is recommended that your parameter map include information on the logical action being performed If including start and end timing, the base implementation of this function will also generate a UUID to store into the MDC for the duration of executable code block IMPORTANT: This function does not handle for nested executeWithContext calls in a single thread. A later release may handle this by merging the inner execution with the current active execution.
      Parameters:
      block - the operation, providing no return value
      parameters - a map of key/value pairs to add to the logging context
      includeTiming - whether to include start, end, and elapsed timing in context

    • executeWithLoggingContext

      void executeWithLoggingContext(org.slf4j.Marker marker, Runnable block, Map<String,String> parameters, boolean includeTiming)
      Sets logging context, executes an operation, and then cleans up logging context Optionally includes start and end timing as well as elapsed time If including start and end timing, elapsed time will be logged from the original start time for each logging statement naturally included in the executable code block. A final log statement at info level will also be provided to show the total execution time at the very end If including start and end timing, it is recommended that your parameter map include information on the logical action being performed If including start and end timing, the base implementation of this function will also generate a UUID to store into the MDC for the duration of executable code block IMPORTANT: This function does not handle for nested executeWithContext calls in a single thread. A later release may handle this by merging the inner execution with the current active execution.
      Parameters:
      marker - marker that uniquely identifies an operation
      block - the operation, providing no return value
      parameters - a map of key/value pairs to add to the logging context
      includeTiming - whether to include start, end, and elapsed timing in context

    • evaluateWithLoggingContext

      Object evaluateWithLoggingContext(Supplier<Object> block, Map<String,String> parameters, boolean includeTiming)
      Sets logging context, executes an operation, and then cleans up logging context and returns the result Optionally includes start and end timing as well as elapsed time. If including start and end timing, elapsed time will be logged from the original start time for each logging statement naturally included in the executable code block. A final log statement at info level will also be provided to show the total execution time at the very end If including start and end timing, it is recommended that your parameter map include information on the logical action being performed If including start and end timing, the base implementation of this function will also generate a UUID to store into the MDC for the duration of executable code block IMPORTANT: This function does not handle for nested evaluateWithContext calls in a single thread. A later release may handle this by merging the inner evaluation with the current active evaluation.
      Parameters:
      block - the operation, providing a return value
      parameters - a map of key/value pairs to add to the logging context
      includeTiming - whether to include start, end, and elapsed timing in context
      Returns:
      an object resulting from the evaluation of the runnable block

    • getCommonParametersForLogMessages

      Map<String,Object> getCommonParametersForLogMessages()
      Allows for the injection of a set of common parameters to be included in all log messages across the application Customers can extend this function to add their own parameters for inclusion. The default implementation returns an empty map IMPORTANT: This method will only cause for a key-value pair to be added to the parameters if a key does not already exist with a non-null value (calls putIfAbsent, not put)
      Returns:
      key-value pairs of the common parameters identified within the function
